thorization2star  aNot only the Jews but Dutch society at large was caught up in a cultural maelstrom between 1880 and 1940. In failing to form a separate pillar in a period when various population groups were doing just that, the Jews were certainly unlike contemporary Catholics or Protestants. In fact, the Jews were not trying to gain entrance in a pre-existing culture but were involved with non-Jews in constructing a new culture. The complexity of Dutch Jewish history once again becomes evident if not new.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aJewsxHistoryxNetherlands. 0aJewsxSocial conditionsxNetherlandsxNiederlandexJudenxNetherlands. 0aJewszNetherlandsxHistory. 0aJewszNetherlandsxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aA.Krop, H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBax, Marty, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerg, Hetty, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrenner, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Julie-Marthe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aE.Zwiep, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrishman, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrishman, Judith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aG.Fuks-Mansfeld, Renate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHofmeester, Karin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoetsenruijter, W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKollatz, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aL.Tananbaum, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c